[Event "Reykjavik World Championship, Game 6"]
[Site "Reykjavik"]
[Date "1972.07.23"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Boris Spassky"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Blurb "Fischer opens 1.c4 for the first time in his life and plays a model positional game. Spassky, the man he was dethroning, applauded from the board when it was over — one of the great sporting moments in chess."]

1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 {The Tartakower Defence — Spassky's solid choice.}
8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. Bb5 a6
15. dxc5 bxc5 16. O-O Ra7 17. Be2 Nd7 18. Nd4 Qf8 19. Nxe6 fxe6 {Fischer trades into a position with a lasting structural edge — Black's e6/d5 pawns are weak.}
20. e4 d4 21. f4 Qe7 22. e5 Rb8 23. Bc4 Kh8 24. Qh3 Nf8 25. b3 a5 26. f5 {The breakthrough — the kingside pawns roll forward.} exf5 27. Rxf5 Nh7 28. Rcf1 Qd8 29. Qg3 Re7 30. h4 Rbb7 31. e6 Rbc7 32. Qe5 Qe8 33. a4 Qd8 34. R1f2 Qe8 35. R2f3 Qd8 36. Bd3 Qe8 37. Qe4 {Every white piece is now perfectly placed for the final blow.} Nf6 38. Rxf6 gxf6 39. Rxf6 Kg8 40. Bc4 Kh8 41. Qf4 {Black resigned — mate on the h6-pawn cannot be stopped. Spassky stood and applauded.}
